        ], 
        "abstract": {
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "paragraph", 
                    "text": "Proteins of the secretin family form large macromolecular complexes, which assemble in the outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria. Secretins are major components of type II and III secretion systems and are linked to extrusion of type IV pili (T4P) and to DNA uptake. By electron cryo-tomography of whole <i>T. thermophilus</i> cells, we determined the <i>in situ</i> structure of a T4P molecular machine in the open and the closed state. Comparison reveals a major conformational change whereby the N-terminal domains of the central secretin PilQ shift by ~30 \u00c5, and two periplasmic gates open to make way for pilus extrusion. Furthermore, we determine the structure of the assembled pilus."
                }
            ]
        }
